body: @daquexian can you please address this? thanks!

@hossein1387 the current support for Android is not complete in the sense that onnxruntime only cross-compiles, but doesn't produce an artifact that can be used on android machines. This issue https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/919 is tracking full support for Android. Please follow that issue.

@hossein1387 @pranavsharma Sorry for the late reply. onnxruntime can compile for Android and a c++ library and also binary files of tests will be produced. The binary files can be executed in adb shell if you pushed it to your Android phone. However, it needs some extra code like jni (Java Native Interface) to make onnxruntime library usable directly in an Android app.

Hi @daquexian, @pranavsharma thanks for your reply. As I said I am confused on what is the output of the build? When I compiled onnxruntime for Android, I did not find any .whl being generated (which is not a surprise to me).

@hossein1387 Python is usually not installed on Android devices. The output is static libraries like libonnxruntime_common.a and libonnxruntime_session.a, and also binaries of tests, like onnxruntime_test_all. These binaries (like onnxruntime_test_all) can be executed in adb shell after pushing it to the device. 

To deploy onnxruntime in an Android app, an Android package (.aar) may be what you wanted. Some extra Java and JNI code are needed to get this .aar file, which currently not exists in onnxruntime and might be added in the progress of #919.

issue.body:
**Description**: 

Add Java API for ONNX Runtime so that Android developers can integrate onnxruntime into their Android apps straightly. https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1180 is a related issue.

The Java API works on my side but there are no unit tests for it yet.
